            </a>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <div class="nav-actions">
          <ThemeToggle variant="segmented" />
          <a href="#install" class="nav-cta">Get Started</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </nav>

    <main data-pagefind-body>
      <section class="hero">
        <div class="container">
          <div class="badge">
            <span class="dot"></span>
            v0.1.1 &middot; OpenAI &middot; Anthropic &middot; any OpenAI-compatible endpoint
          </div>
          <h1>
            One Go client.<br />
            <span class="gradient">Every LLM provider.</span>
          </h1>
          <p class="subtitle">
            <strong>llmrouter</strong> is a streaming-first Go library
            that gives you an OpenAI-shaped API for OpenAI, Anthropic,
            and any OpenAI-compatible endpoint &mdash; with
            byte-passthrough for building gateways and proxies.
          </p>
          <div class="install-highlight">
            <div class="install-box">
              <code><span class="prompt">$</span> go get github.com/elloloop/llmrouter@v0.1.1</code>
              <button class="copy-btn" data-copy="go get github.com/elloloop/llmrouter@v0.1.1">
                Copy
              </button>
            </div>
            <span class="install-platforms-hero">
              Go 1.23+ &middot; Apache-2.0 &middot; stdlib + <code>google/uuid</code> only
            </span>
          </div>
          <div class="hero-buttons">
            <a href="/llmrouter/docs/" class="btn btn-primary">
              Read the Docs
              <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="2" stroke="currentColor" aria-hidden="true">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M13.5 4.5 21 12m0 0-7.5 7.5M21 12H3" />
              </svg>
            </a>
            <a
              href="https://github.com/elloloop/llmrouter"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener"
              class="btn btn-secondary"
            >
              <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="currentColor" aria-hidden="true">
                <path d="M12 .3a12 12 0 0 0-3.8 23.38c.6.12.83-.26.83-.57L9 20.85c-3.43.75-4.15-1.65-4.15-1.65-.55-1.41-1.35-1.78-1.35-1.78-1.1-.76.09-.74.09-.74 1.22.09 1.87 1.25 1.87 1.25 1.08 1.86 2.84 1.32 3.53 1.01.11-.78.42-1.32.77-1.62-2.74-.31-5.62-1.37-5.62-6.1 0-1.35.48-2.45 1.27-3.31-.13-.31-.55-1.57.12-3.26 0 0 1.03-.33 3.38 1.26a11.74 11.74 0 0 1 6.16 0c2.34-1.6 3.37-1.26 3.37-1.26.67 1.69.25 2.95.12 3.26.8.86 1.27 1.96 1.27 3.31 0 4.74-2.89 5.79-5.64 6.09.44.38.84 1.13.84 2.28l-.01 3.38c0 .31.22.69.84.57A12 12 0 0 0 12 .3" />
              </svg>
              GitHub
            </a>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="why-section" id="why">
        <div class="container">
          <p class="section-label reveal">Why llmrouter</p>
          <h2 class="section-heading reveal">
            Three properties. That&rsquo;s the whole pitch.
          </h2>
          <p class="section-sub reveal">
            Most multi-LLM libraries reach for breadth. llmrouter is
            narrower and more opinionated &mdash; designed around the
            shape of code that has to ship to production.
          </p>
          <div class="pillars reveal">
            <article class="pillar">
              <div class="pillar-icon">S</div>
              <h3>Streaming-first</h3>
              <p>
                Channel-based deltas with a producer goroutine and
                proper <code>context.Context</code> cancellation that
                propagates all the way to the in-flight HTTP request.
                Cancel the context and the upstream connection closes
                &mdash; no leaked goroutines, no orphaned token spend.
              </p>
            </article>
            <article class="pillar">
              <div class="pillar-icon">B</div>
              <h3>Byte passthrough</h3>
              <p>
                Every chunk preserves its original wire bytes via
                <code>Chunk.Raw</code>. Build proxies and gateways
                that are byte-identical to upstream OpenAI without
                re-marshalling typed structs &mdash; the bytes you
                forward downstream are the bytes you received.
              </p>
            </article>
            <article class="pillar">
              <div class="pillar-icon">D</div>
              <h3>Boring dependencies</h3>
              <p>
                The only dependencies are the Go standard library
                and <code>google/uuid</code>. No surprise transitive
                trees. New providers will only ever pull in their
                official vendor SDK &mdash; published by Google, AWS,
                Anthropic, or OpenAI.
              </p>
            </article>
          </div>
          <div class="why-cta reveal">
            <strong>llmrouter</strong> is the library a gateway is
            built on top of &mdash; not the gateway itself.
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="features" id="features">
        <div class="container">
          <p class="section-label reveal">What you get today</p>
          <h2 class="section-heading reveal">Two providers, one shape, zero surprises.</h2>
          <p class="section-sub reveal">
            v0.1 ships OpenAI and Anthropic with full request and SSE
            translation. v0.2 brings Azure OpenAI Service, AWS
            Bedrock, and Google Vertex AI.
          </p>
          <div class="features-grid reveal">
            <article class="feature-card">
              <div class="feature-icon">OA</div>
              <h3>OpenAI, passthrough</h3>
              <p>
                Default provider. Streaming chat completions against
                <code>/v1/chat/completions</code>. Request bytes and
                chunk bytes pass through unchanged when you set
                <code>Raw</code> &mdash; ideal for proxies.
              </p>
            </article>
            <article class="feature-card">
              <div class="feature-icon">URL</div>
              <h3>Any OpenAI-compatible endpoint</h3>
              <p>
                One <code>WithBaseURL</code> call points the OpenAI
                provider at OpenRouter, Together, Groq, vLLM, Ollama,
                LM Studio, or your private model behind a firewall.
                No new SDK per vendor.
              </p>
            </article>
            <article class="feature-card">
              <div class="feature-icon">AN</div>
              <h3>Anthropic, translated</h3>
              <p>
                Anthropic <code>/v1/messages</code> with full
                bidirectional translation &mdash; OpenAI request
                shape on the way in, Anthropic SSE events
                (<code>message_start</code>,
                <code>content_block_delta</code>, &hellip;) translated
                back to OpenAI chunks on the way out.
              </p>
            </article>
            <article class="feature-card">
              <div class="feature-icon">v02</div>
              <h3>Cloud triple on the roadmap</h3>
              <p>
                v0.2 lands Azure OpenAI Service (deployment URL +
                <code>api-key</code> header), AWS Bedrock (SigV4 +
                per-model-family body translation), and Google
                Vertex AI (ADC auth, project/region).
              </p>
            </article>
            <article class="feature-card">
              <div class="feature-icon">330</div>
              <h3>Tested to the wire</h3>
              <p>
                330-subtest table-driven test suite. 100% statement
                coverage on the core; 90.4% on each provider. All
                tests run race-clean
                (<code>go test -race</code>).
              </p>
            </article>
            <article class="feature-card">
              <div class="feature-icon">A2</div>
              <h3>Apache-2.0, pre-1.0</h3>
              <p>
                Apache-2.0 licensed. Currently v0.1.x &mdash; expect
                minor API churn between minor versions until v1.0
                freezes the surface. Patch versions never break the
                API.
              </p>
            </article>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="quickstart-section" id="quickstart">
        <div class="container">
          <p class="section-label reveal">Quick start</p>
          <h2 class="section-heading reveal">
            From <code>go get</code> to streaming tokens in 40 lines.
          </h2>
          <p class="section-sub reveal">
            Open a streaming chat completion, print each delta as it
            arrives, exit on a clean close. The same code runs
            against any OpenAI-compatible endpoint.
          </p>
          <div class="code-wrap reveal">
            <Code lang="go" code={quickstartCode} />
          </div>
          <p class="section-sub reveal sub-spaced">
            Want Anthropic instead? Swap the import and the model id
            &mdash; the loop, the request shape, and the consumer
            don&rsquo;t change.
          </p>
          <div class="code-wrap reveal">
            <Code lang="go" code={anthropicCode} />
          </div>
          <div class="quickstart-cta reveal">
            <a href="/llmrouter/docs/quickstart" class="btn btn-primary">
              Full quick-start guide
              <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="2" stroke="currentColor" aria-hidden="true">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M13.5 4.5 21 12m0 0-7.5 7.5M21 12H3" />
              </svg>
            </a>
            <a href="/llmrouter/docs/concepts/byte-passthrough" class="btn btn-secondary">
              Byte passthrough
            </a>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="providers-section" id="providers">
        <div class="container">
          <p class="section-label reveal">Providers</p>
          <h2 class="section-heading reveal">One <code>Provider</code> interface. Many backends.</h2>
          <p class="section-sub reveal">
            Each provider implements the same one-method interface.
            Your application code never branches on which one is
            upstream.
          </p>
          <div class="providers-grid reveal">
            <article class="provider-card shipped">
              <div class="provider-tag">Shipped</div>
              <h3>OpenAI</h3>
              <p>
                <code>providers/openai</code>. Default, passthrough,
                works with any OpenAI-compatible endpoint via
                <code>WithBaseURL</code>.
              </p>
              <a href="/llmrouter/docs/providers/openai" class="provider-link">
                Read the docs &rarr;
              </a>
            </article>
            <article class="provider-card shipped">
              <div class="provider-tag">Shipped</div>
              <h3>Anthropic</h3>
              <p>
                <code>providers/anthropic</code>. Full
                <code>/v1/messages</code> request and SSE translation.
                <code>MaxTokens</code> required on the request.
              </p>
              <a href="/llmrouter/docs/providers/anthropic" class="provider-link">
                Read the docs &rarr;
              </a>
            </article>
            <article class="provider-card shipped">
              <div class="provider-tag">Shipped</div>
              <h3>Any OpenAI-compatible</h3>
              <p>
                OpenRouter, Together, Groq, vLLM, Ollama, LM Studio,
                anything else that speaks OpenAI SSE. One
                <code>WithBaseURL</code> call.
              </p>
              <a href="/llmrouter/docs/providers/openai-compatible" class="provider-link">
                See examples &rarr;
              </a>
            </article>
            <article class="provider-card planned">
              <div class="provider-tag planned-tag">v0.2</div>
              <h3>Azure OpenAI Service</h3>
              <p>
                Deployment URL + <code>api-key</code> header +
                <code>api-version</code> query param. Same OpenAI
                request and response shape underneath.
              </p>
              <span class="provider-link muted">Coming in v0.2</span>
            </article>
            <article class="provider-card planned">
              <div class="provider-tag planned-tag">v0.2</div>
              <h3>AWS Bedrock</h3>
              <p>
                SigV4 request signing, per-model-family body
                translation: Claude / Llama / Titan.
              </p>
              <span class="provider-link muted">Coming in v0.2</span>
            </article>
            <article class="provider-card planned">
              <div class="provider-tag planned-tag">v0.2</div>
              <h3>Google Vertex AI</h3>
              <p>
                ADC auth, project + region in the endpoint URL.
                Vertex&rsquo; streaming surface translated to
                OpenAI chunks.
              </p>
              <span class="provider-link muted">Coming in v0.2</span>
            </article>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="stats">
        <div class="container">
          <div class="stats-grid reveal">
            <div>
              <div class="stat-value">v0.1.1</div>
              <div class="stat-label">Latest release</div>
            </div>
            <div>
              <div class="stat-value">330</div>
              <div class="stat-label">Table-driven subtests</div>
            </div>
            <div>
              <div class="stat-value">100%</div>
              <div class="stat-label">Core coverage</div>
            </div>
            <div>
              <div class="stat-value">2 + N</div>
              <div class="stat-label">Providers (OpenAI, Anthropic, + any OpenAI-compatible)</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="install-section" id="install">
        <div class="container">
          <div class="install-block reveal">
            <h2>Install in one line.</h2>
            <p class="install-sub">Go 1.23+. Apache-2.0. No surprises in your <code>go.sum</code>.</p>
            <div class="install-cmd">
              <code><span class="prompt">$</span> go get github.com/elloloop/llmrouter@v0.1.1</code>
              <button class="copy-btn" data-copy="go get github.com/elloloop/llmrouter@v0.1.1">Copy</button>
            </div>
            <p class="install-platforms">
              Then head to the
              <a href="/llmrouter/docs/quickstart">quick-start guide</a>
              for the canonical OpenAI &amp; Anthropic walkthroughs,
              or read the
              <a href="/llmrouter/docs/project/comparison">comparison
              vs alternatives</a> if you&rsquo;re still evaluating.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>
    </main>

    <footer>
      <div class="container footer-inner">
        <div class="footer-left">
          <a href="/llmrouter/" class="footer-logo"><span>&gt;</span> llmrouter</a>
          <span class="footer-text">Open source &middot; Apache-2.0</span>
        </div>
        <div class="footer-links">
          <a href="/llmrouter/docs/">Docs</a>
          <a href="https://github.com/elloloop/llmrouter" target="_blank" rel="noopener">GitHub</a>
          <a href="https://github.com/elloloop/llmrouter/releases" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Releases</a>
          <a href="https://pkg.go.dev/github.com/elloloop/llmrouter" target="_blank" rel="noopener">pkg.go.dev</a>
          <a href="https://github.com/elloloop/llmrouter/issues" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Issues</a>
          <a href="https://github.com/elloloop/llmrouter/blob/main/LICENSE" target="_blank" rel="noopener">License</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </footer>

    <script>
      document.querySelectorAll(".copy-btn").forEach((btn) => {
        btn.addEventListener("click", () => {
          const text = btn.getAttribute("data-copy") || "";
          navigator.clipboard.writeText(text).then(() => {
            btn.textContent = "Copied";
            window.setTimeout(() => {
              btn.textContent = "Copy";
            }, 2000);
          });
        });
      });

      const reveals = document.querySelectorAll(".reveal");
      const observer = new IntersectionObserver(
        (entries) => {
          entries.forEach((entry) => {
            if (!entry.isIntersecting) return;
            entry.target.classList.add("visible");
            observer.unobserve(entry.target);
          });
        },
        { threshold: 0.1 },
      );
      reveals.forEach((el) => observer.observe(el));
    </script>
  </body>
</html>

<style is:global>
  :root,
  .dark {
    --dp-bg: #0a0a0a;
    --dp-bg-secondary: #111111;
    --dp-bg-tertiary: #171717;
    --dp-bg-hover: #1c1c1c;
    --dp-bg-active: #222222;
    --dp-border: #262626;
    --dp-border-subtle: #1a1a1a;
    --dp-text: #e5e5e5;
    --dp-text-secondary: #a3a3a3;
    --dp-text-tertiary: #525252;
    --dp-accent: #ffffff;
    --dp-accent-hover: #e5e5e5;
    --dp-accent-contrast: #0a0a0a;
    --dp-success: #22c55e;
    --dp-error: #ef4444;
    --dp-warning: #f59e0b;
    --dp-info: #a3a3a3;
  }

  .light {
    --dp-bg: #ffffff;
    --dp-bg-secondary: #fafafa;
    --dp-bg-tertiary: #f5f5f5;
    --dp-bg-hover: #eeeeee;
    --dp-bg-active: #e5e5e5;
    --dp-border: #d4d4d4;
    --dp-border-subtle: #e5e5e5;
    --dp-text: #0a0a0a;
    --dp-text-secondary: #525252;
    --dp-text-tertiary: #a3a3a3;
    --dp-accent: #0a0a0a;
    --dp-accent-hover: #171717;
    --dp-accent-contrast: #ffffff;
    --dp-success: #16a34a;
    --dp-error: #dc2626;
    --dp-warning: #d97706;
    --dp-info: #525252;
  }

  .landing-page *,
  .landing-page *::before,
  .landing-page *::after {
    box-sizing: border-box;
  }

  .landing-page {
    margin: 0;
    background: var(--dp-bg);
    color: var(--dp-text);
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    line-height: 1.6;
    overflow-x: hidden;
  }

  .landing-page code,
